prompt:
Our laser cutter's job files are JSON and the shop-floor software that consumes them diffs raw payloads between the design station and the controller, so serialization has to be byte-for-byte stable. I'm replacing a pile of hand-rolled JsonDocument walking with System.Text.Json's own polymorphism support — attributes on the model, not a home-made dispatcher. C# / .NET 10, namespace LaserJob, one project. JobFileTests.cs is the wire contract; leave it, the csproj, and .gitignore alone.

The model: abstract record JobStep is the base, wearing [JsonPolymorphic]/[JsonDerivedType] so the discriminator property is "op" and it LEADS every object on the wire. Three step kinds:
- CutStep(string Path, Speed Feed, int Passes) — op "cut", wire {"op":"cut","path":"outline.svg","feed":"120mm/s","passes":2}
- EngraveStep(string Path, int Dpi, Speed Feed) — op "engrave", wire {"op":"engrave","path":"logo.png","dpi":300,"feed":"85.5mm/s"}
- PauseStep(string Message) — op "pause", wire {"op":"pause","message":"flip the sheet"}
Property names are camelCase on the wire (naming policy, not renamed properties), compact output (no indentation).

Speed is NOT a raw number in the model: readonly record struct Speed(decimal MmPerSecond) with a custom JsonConverter<Speed> hung on it via [JsonConverter]. On the wire it's the string "<decimal>mm/s" — invariant culture in BOTH directions no matter what the thread culture is (a controller imaged with a comma-decimal locale once wrote feeds the firmware refused; one test flips CurrentCulture to de-DE to make sure that never comes back). Reading: a JSON token that isn't a string fails with a JsonException whose message is exactly "speed must be a string like '120mm/s'"; a string that isn't a decimal followed by mm/s (wrong units, garbage text) fails with JsonException, message exactly "invalid speed '<the raw string>'".

Entry point the tools use: static class JobFile with string Serialize(IReadOnlyList<JobStep> steps) and IReadOnlyList<JobStep> Deserialize(string json). A job round-trips exactly both ways: objects -> wire -> equal objects, wire -> objects -> identical bytes. Unrecognized "op" values must surface as a JsonException naming the bad id; a payload with no "op" at all is the serializer's polymorphism complaint (NotSupportedException mentioning the type discriminator) — don't swallow either. `dotnet test` green means the controller and the design station agree forever.
